In **Scenario A**, I used role assignment by stating that it needs to be answered by a science teacher who teaches and understands 10 year olds and then asking the model to explain nuclear reactions to a curious 10-year-old who had never studied science before. This provided context about the audience's age and knowledge level, which resulted in a simpler, more engaging explanation that used analogies and avoided technical jargon.

In **Scenario C**, I used role assignment by stating i was the top .1% branding expert in India and then context setting was set by specifying that the target audience was Gen-Z consumers living in Tier 1 cities and that the taglines should be funny, culturally relevant, and use Gen-Z lingo. This additional background information helped the model generate marketing taglines that were more creative, relatable, and tailored to the intended audience.

Overall, role assignment helped the model to add a level of expertise in the output, while context setting provided the necessary information to create outputs that were more relevant, targeted, and effective and adapt its communication style to the audience

